ut the Book0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhere are Asian Americans gaining political power in the United States today? And how? Looking beyond traditional conceptions of immigrant political behavior in "gateway" cities, James Lai comprehensively analyzes how Asian Americans are not only winning elected office, but also sustaining representation, in places as diverse as California, Texas, Wisconsin, and Maryland. Lai's multidimensional approach and vivid case studies illustrate both the unique characteristics and the political commonalities of Asian communities throughout the United States: their core populations, civic organizations, political leanings, and specific electoral challenges and successes. The result is a complex portrait of the breadth of Asian American participation in contemporary multiracial politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAsian AmericansxCase studiesxPolitics and government. 0aAsian AmericansxPolitics and governmentvCase studies. 0aAsian AmericansxPolitics and government. 0aImmigrantsxPolitical activityxUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aPolitical participationxUnited States. 0aPolitical participationzUnited States. 0aSuburban lifexUnited States. 0aSuburban lifezUnited States. 0aSuburbsxUnited States. 0aSuburbszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertLynne Rienner Press Complete eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078425140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978162637291740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781626372917423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781626372917/original  a978-3-11-078425-1  Lynne Rienner Press Complete eBook-Package 2013-2000